close_reason: Delivered and verified schema evolution SDK/CLI migrations with packed and 100k acceptance evidence.
body: "Schema commands today mutate only the schema definition (types.json/fields.json/statuses): after a rename or retirement, existing items silently keep stale type names, field keys, and status values, and nothing re-validates or migrates them. A workspace spanning decades will evolve its custom schema many times, so schema evolution without data migration quietly corrupts the long tail — exactly the data the memory-tier and time-travel features (pm-5qmm, pm-hib1) later depend on.\n\nProposal: schema-evolution migration primitives, SDK-first (extends the pm-3mna schema surface; the CLI verb is presentation):\n- rename-type <old> <new>: moves item files/folders, rewrites type fields, updates workflows/profiles referencing the type.\n- rename-field <old> <new> [--type T]: rewrites the field key across affected items; collision with reserved/built-in names refused (pm-b9ov class).\n- remap-status / retire-status --map old=new: rewrites status values with an explicit total mapping; refuses partial mappings.\n- Every touched item gets a history entry recording before/after (the immutable-proof invariant holds through migrations); the workspace-scoped stream (pm-klo8) records the schema mutation itself.\n- --dry-run prints the full migration plan (affected counts, per-change detail) for review; execution is resumable/atomic-per-item so a crash never leaves an untracked half-migrated state.\n- Scale: candidate selection via the derived read index (pm-801d) so cost is O(affected); format_version gating precedent from pm-0qg5 applies if layout changes.\n\nRelation to existing work: pm-z5nb covers schema CRUD completion (remove-type, add-status, per-type workflows) — this item covers what happens to already-written items when the schema changes underneath them. pm-d1ig scaffolds extension-side migration starters; this is the workspace-side primitive."
